sec.p:
This article studies the material possibilities of all normative theories of justice. Most philosophical discussions of justice present, interpret, defend, infer, or criticize particular theories of justice. Most of these discussions have been ideal, from Plato to Rawls and beyond. Ideal principles and systems of justice need not consider whether they or their reasonable approximations are materially possible in various social contexts because ideals exist on a different ontological plain. The ideal approach to the philosophical examination of justice has come under increasing criticism recently (for example, 
Farrelly, 2007; 
Mills, 2005).

Common law recognizes the roughness (the margins of error) of justice implicitly in the principles of the presumption of innocence, the benefit of the doubt, the assignment of the burden of proof, and the demand for proof beyond reasonable doubt. These principles shift the margins of error (the inaccuracies) in the direction of acquitting the guilty to reduce errors in the direction of convicting the innocent. Ceteris paribus, the higher is the standard of proof in retributive justice, the higher will be the ratio of erroneous convictions to erroneous acquittals (
DeKay, 1996: 95; 
Laudan, 2006: 30, 68).
